Mismediation

John Flournoy

12/27/2017

How often do you see evidence for mediation from a statistical test when in fact the data generating process is purely correlational?

Generating the data

library(lavaan)
library(simsem)
library(semPlot)

The data generating model specifies three variables over 3 waves. Each is correlated with the other at r = .5, and fairly stable, with an autoregressive path-weight of .7.

generatingModel <- '

#2 on 1
y2 ~ .7*y1
x2 ~ .7*x1
z2 ~ .7*z1
y2 ~ 0*x1 + 0*z1
x2 ~ 0*y1 + 0*z1
z2 ~ 0*y1 + 0*x1

#3 on 2
y3 ~ .7*y2
x3 ~ .7*x2
z3 ~ .7*z2
y3 ~ 0*x2 + 0*z2
x3 ~ 0*y2 + 0*z2
z3 ~ 0*y2 + 0*x2

#wave cors
y1 ~~ .5*x1 + .5*z1
x1 ~~ .5*z1
y2 ~~ .5*x2 + .5*z2
x2 ~~ .5*z2
y3 ~~ .5*x3 + .5*z3
x3 ~~ .5*z3

#Resid
y1 ~~ 1*y1
x1 ~~ 1*x1
z1 ~~ 1*z1
y2 ~~ 1*y2
x2 ~~ 1*x2
z2 ~~ 1*z2
y3 ~~ 1*y3
x3 ~~ 1*x3
z3 ~~ 1*z3
'

generatingModelEst <- '

#2 on 1
y2 ~ y1
x2 ~ x1
z2 ~ z1
y2 ~ x1 + z1
x2 ~ y1 + z1
z2 ~ y1 + x1

#3 on 2
y3 ~ y2
x3 ~ x2
z3 ~ z2
y3 ~ x2 + z2
x3 ~ y2 + z2
z3 ~ y2 + x2

#wave cors
y1 ~~ x1 + z1
x1 ~~ z1
y2 ~~ x2 + z2
x2 ~~ z2
y3 ~~ x3 + z3
x3 ~~ z3

#Resid
y1 ~~ y1
x1 ~~ x1
z1 ~~ z1
y2 ~~ y2
x2 ~~ x2
z2 ~~ z2
y3 ~~ y3
x3 ~~ x3
z3 ~~ z3
'

Misspecified statistical models

Looking for mediation when the null of no mediation is true can be thought of as estimating a misspecified model. Im going to concentrate just on the significance of the parameter that estimates the mediated effect, since this is often what people do (rarely is model comparison used, and in cross-sectional data it can be shown that a mediation model is just-identified anyway).

We can check out a few misspecifications. First, well test the best case scenario short of testing the true model. In mediationModelControlzT1 we do the usual longitudinal best-practice of regressing our wave 2 dependent variable on its wave 1 measurement (y2 ~ y1 + c*x1 + b*z2, where c and b are just the typical labels of the direct paths between the predictor and outcome, and mediator and outcome). In the regression of our wave 2 mediator on the independent variable, we can also include the mediators wave 1 measurement (z2 ~ a*x1 + z1, where a is just the typical label of the path from predictor to mediator). Conceptually, weve made sure to account for stability within each variable over time cross-sectional models of mediation dont do this.

In the two other misspecified models, we additionally leave out the measurement of the mediator at wave 1, and then also leave out the measurement of the dependent variable at wave 1. We can also look at the cross-sectional mediation model, and a longitudinal mediational model written without any information about previous measurement.

#Each of these does not correctly capture the data generating model specified previously
mediationModelControlzT1 <- ' #2-wave model accounting for prior levels
y2 ~ y1 + c*x1 + b*z2
z2 ~ a*x1 + z1
# indirect effect (a*b)
ab := a*b
# total effect
total := c + (a*b)
'
mediationModelNoControlzT1 <- '#2-wave model, no control for mediator previous level
y2 ~ y1 + c*x1 + b*z2
z2 ~ a*x1  
# indirect effect (a*b)
ab := a*b
# total effect
total := c + (a*b)
'
mediationModelNoControlzOryT1 <- '#2-wave, no control for mediator or outcome previous level
y2 ~ c*x1 + b*z2
z2 ~ a*x1  
# indirect effect (a*b)
ab := a*b
# total effect
total := c + (a*b)
'
mediationModelCrossSection <- '#Cross sectional mediation
y3 ~ c*x3 + b*z3
z3 ~ a*x3
#indirect
ab := a*b
#total
total := c + (a*b)'

mediationBadLong <- '#3-wave, no control for mediator or outcome previous level
y3 ~ c*x1 + b*z2
z2 ~ a*x1
#indirect
ab := a*b
#total
total := c + (a*b)'

Before running a buch of simulations, Ill make sure the models are as expected by generating a single set, and fitting the above. I wont show the output because its rather lengthy.

someData <- simulateData(model=generatingModel, sample.nobs=250, empirical=T)
fit.DGM <- sem(generatingModelEst, someData, fixed.x=F)
summary(fit.DGM, standardized=T)

fit.CtrlT1.yz <- sem(mediationModelControlzT1, someData)
summary(fit.CtrlT1.yz, standardized = T)

fit.noCtrlT1.z <- sem(mediationModelNoControlzT1, someData)
summary(fit.noCtrlT1.z, standardized = T)

fit.noCtrlT1.yz <- sem(mediationModelNoControlzOryT1, someData)
summary(fit.noCtrlT1.yz, standardized = T)

fit.CrossSection <- sem(mediationModelCrossSection, someData)
summary(fit.CrossSection, standardized = T)

fit.BadLong <- sem(mediationBadLong, someData)
summary(fit.BadLong, standardized = T)

Power to detect mediation (when the null is true)

You can see that were getting a hint that the ab path might be getting bigger as we further misspecify the model. To find out for sure, lets run the simulations. Our outcome of interest will be the measure of power to detect a significant ab path the mediated effect. Usually power is a good thing, but if you have power to detect something thats not there, its an indication that your model is reliably giving you the wrong answer.

REDOSIMS=F
if(REDOSIMS){
    sim.CtrlT1.yz <- simsem::sim(nRep=1000, 
                                 model=mediationModelControlzT1, 
                                 n=250,

Looking across those ab lines, you see that were not too bad off if we control for our wave 1 measurements. However, if we dont do that, we end up with massive power to detect a significant mediation. To me, this warrants extreme caution.

Mediation package?

Theres a cool package called mediation written by some experts in causal inference. Ive used it in a paper. I only controlled for the previous level of the outcome variable. Does this packages machinations obviate any of the issues with causal inference in mediation illustrated above? Lets find out!

library(mediation)

crosssectionMediateModel <- function(aDF){
    model.m <- lm(z2 ~ x2, data = aDF)
    model.y <- lm(y2 ~ x2 + z2, data = aDF)
    
    mediateModel <- try(mediate(model.m = model.m, model.y = model.y, 
                            sims = 500, boot = F,
                            treat = 'x2', mediator = 'z2'))
    if (identical(class(mediateModel), "try-error")){
        rezlist <- list(coef = NA, se = NA, converged = FALSE)
    } else {
        coefVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0, d1 = mediateModel$d0, 
                     z0 = mediateModel$z0, z1 = mediateModel$d0,
                     n0 = mediateModel$n0, n1 = mediateModel$n0)
        
        seVec <- c(d0 = NA, d1 = NA, 
                   z0 = NA, z1 = NA,
                   n0 = NA, n1 = NA)
        
        cilowerVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]], d1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]], 
                        z0 = mediateModel$z0.ci[[1]], z1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]],
                        n0 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[1]], n1 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[1]])
        
        ciupperVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]], d1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]], 
                        z0 = mediateModel$z0.ci[[2]], z1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]],
                        n0 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[2]], n1 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[2]])
        
        rezList <- list(coef = coefVec, se = seVec, cilower = cilowerVec, ciupper = ciupperVec, converged = TRUE)
    }
    
    return(rezList)
}

anOutfun <- function(obj){
    acmeNotZero <- !(all(obj$ciupper['d0'] >= 0, obj$cilower['d0'] <= 0))
}

if(REDOSIMS){
    mediatePkgCrossSection <- simsem::sim(nRep = 8*10, n = 200, generate = generatingModel, 
                                          model = crosssectionMediateModel,
                                          multicore = TRUE, outfun = anOutfun)
    saveRDS(mediatePkgCrossSection, 'mediatePkgCrossSection.RDS')
} else {
    mediatePkgCrossSection <- readRDS('mediatePkgCrossSection.RDS')
}

So using this package doesnt help at all in cross-sectional data. We can examine the case with appropriate controls for previous levels as well, to make sure that this may help across techniques.

controlPrevWaveMediateModel <- function(aDF){
    model.m <- lm(z2 ~ z1 + x1, data = aDF)
    model.y <- lm(y2 ~ y1 + x1 + z2, data = aDF)
    
    mediateModel <- try(mediate(model.m = model.m, model.y = model.y, 
                            sims = 500, boot = F,
                            treat = 'x1', mediator = 'z2'))
    if (identical(class(mediateModel), "try-error")){
        rezlist <- list(coef = NA, se = NA, converged = FALSE)
    } else {
        coefVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0, d1 = mediateModel$d0, 
                     z0 = mediateModel$z0, z1 = mediateModel$d0,
                     n0 = mediateModel$n0, n1 = mediateModel$n0)
        
        seVec <- c(d0 = NA, d1 = NA, 
                   z0 = NA, z1 = NA,
                   n0 = NA, n1 = NA)
        
        cilowerVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]], d1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]], 
                        z0 = mediateModel$z0.ci[[1]], z1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[1]],
                        n0 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[1]], n1 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[1]])
        
        ciupperVec <- c(d0 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]], d1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]], 
                        z0 = mediateModel$z0.ci[[2]], z1 = mediateModel$d0.ci[[2]],
                        n0 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[2]], n1 = mediateModel$n0.ci[[2]])
        
        rezList <- list(coef = coefVec, se = seVec, cilower = cilowerVec, ciupper = ciupperVec, converged = TRUE)
    }
    
    return(rezList)
}

##    5. At least one correlation estimates were greater than 1 or less than -1 = 0 
##    6. Model-implied covariance matrices of any groups of latent variables are not positive definite = 0 
## NOTE: The data generation model is not the same as the analysis model. See the summary of the population underlying data generation by the summaryPopulation function.
cat(paste0("Proportion of simulations that reject null of no mediation: ",
           mediationPower <- sum(unlist(getExtraOutput(mediatePkgControlPrev)))/mediatePkgControlPrev@nRep))
## Proportion of simulations that reject null of no mediation: 0.0625

This should be around .05, which is the false-positive rate we expect (this is a small number of simulations, 80, so it easily could be a bit above or below).

Conclusion

Using the two most common methods Ive seen to assess mediation (path-tracing, or the mediation package), cross-sectional data will produce evidence of mediation when there is no actual mediation. We know there is no actual mediation because weve created the data such that each variable is only conditional on its previous level, and not at all on the measurements of the other variables.

For further reading about mediation as one of a family of causal claims, check out

Bullock, J. G., Green, D. P., & Ha, S. E. (2010). Yes, but whats the mechanism? (dont expect an easy answer). Journal of Personality and Social Psychology, 98(4), 550558. http://doi.org/10.1037/a0018933
